Carbamic acid has hydrogen bonding capabilities that significantly increase its melting point. The dimethyl cyanimidodithiocarbonate substitutes the primary amine with a cyano group and also contains thiol groups instead of hydroxyl groups. These changes will decrease the melting capability of hydrogen bonds and the potential for intermolecular interactions due to the cyano and thiol groups, respectively. The presence of sulfur in thiol groups compared to oxygen in hydroxyl groups would typically decrease the melting point due to the larger, more polarizable atom leading to lower intermolecular forces; the effect of two thiol groups may be approximated at -30°C each. The overall predicted decrease from the reference compound would then be -100°C.
